al reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Require the third-party provider to implement multi-factor authentication for all employee accounts. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Mandate a yearly penetration test of the third-party provider’s systems by an independent security firm. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Negotiate a higher level of financial compensation in the service level agreement (SLA) to cover potential damages from data breaches. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-01206', 5, 'Medium', 'Data Loss Prevention', 'What is the PRIMARY concern for the auditor regarding this practice?', 'The potential for employees to accidentally delete or corrupt the extracted data.', 'The lack of traceability and accountability for the extracted customer data, increasing the risk of unauthorized disclosure.', 'The inefficiency of exporting data in plain text format, consuming unnecessary network bandwidth.', 'The potential for the extracted data to become outdated and inaccurate over time.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): The lack of traceability and accountability for the extracted customer data, increasing the risk of unauthorized disclosure.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: The potential for employees to accidentally delete or corrupt the extracted data. → This approach 