  ('CISA-01241', 5, 'Hard', 'Incident Investigation and Forensics', 'What is the auditor''s MOST pressing concern regarding the company''s forensic investigation capabilities?', 'The potential legal ramifications of the data leak, including potential violations of intellectual property laws and regulatory requirements.', 'The lack of a documented chain of custody procedure for handling compromised devices and preserving evidence.', 'The difficulty in determining the full scope of the data leak and identifying all affected intellectual property due to insufficient evidence.', 'The cost associated with engaging external forensic experts to recover potentially lost data from wiped hard drives.', 'C', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (C): The difficulty in determining the full scope of the data leak and identifying all affected intellectual property due to insufficient evidence.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance pu