  ('CISA-01255', 5, 'Hard', 'Incident Investigation and Forensics', 'What control should the auditor FIRST evaluate to determine the effectiveness of the incident response in this situation?', 'The effectiveness of the DLP system''s configuration to prevent data exfiltration by authorized users.', 'The completeness and accuracy of the termination checklist to ensure revocation of access rights.', 'The procedures for conducting exit interviews with departing employees to ascertain potential security risks.', 'The timely execution and documentation of the incident response plan, including containment, eradication, and recovery steps.', 'D', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (D): The timely execution and documentation of the incident response plan, including containment, eradication, and recovery steps.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''r