ices. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Mandate annual security awareness training for all employees participating in the BYOD program. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Restrict access to sensitive patient data to hospital-owned devices only. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.', 'Implementing DLP controls within the VDI environment directly addresses the risk of data exfiltration regardless of the device used to access the VDI. It provides a technical control to prevent data leakage at the source, regardless of user actions or device security.', 'See reasoning above for explanation of correct vs incorrect choices', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Implement strong DLP controls within the VDI environment to prevent unauthorized data exfiltration.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources 