  ('CISA-01326', 1, 'Medium', 'Ethics', 'What should the information systems auditor FIRST consider when evaluating the ethical implications of this new system?', 'The cost-effectiveness of the facial recognition system compared to traditional attendance methods.', 'Whether the system complies with all applicable data privacy laws and regulations, and if students have been provided with adequate notice and consent mechanisms.', 'The technical specifications and security features of the facial recognition software to prevent unauthorized access.', 'The potential impact of the system on student morale and academic performance.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Whether the system complies with all applicable data privacy laws and regulations, and if students have been provided with adequate notice and consent mechanisms.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ I