ding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: The cost-effectiveness of the facial recognition system compared to traditional attendance methods. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: The technical specifications and security features of the facial recognition software to prevent unauthorized access. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: The potential impact of the system on student morale and academic performance. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-01327', 1, 'Hard', 'Follow-up', 'A CISA professional, in reviewing the audit results of a high-frequency trading platform at a stock exchange, notes a significant increase in rejected order rates alongside a documented decrease in average trade execution latency. The initial audit scope focused on system performance and regulatory compliance. What is the MOST important follow-up action for the CISA professional to undertake?', 'Expand the audit scope to include an assessment of the algorithms used for order routing and execution logic to identify potential manipulation vulnerabilities.', 'Immediately escalate the findings to senior management and the regulatory body, as the increased rejection rate indicates a definite system failure.', 'Reduce the sample size for testing during subsequent audits, as the initial findings clearly demonstrate system instability.', 'Recommend a comprehensive hardware upgrade to further reduce latency, regardless of the underlying cause of the rejection rate increase.', 'A', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (A): Expand the audit scope to include an assessment of the algorithms used for order routing and execution logic to identify potential manipulation vulnerabilities.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This 